      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":370,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed — first 5 minutes should feel almost too easy. Let your body wake up gradually.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable, conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences throughout. This is aerobic base building — resist the urge to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace for the final 5 minutes. Follow with light dynamic stretching, paying attention to your IT band and hip flexors given your history.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of brisk walking or very easy jogging. Add 4–5 dynamic movements: leg swings, hip circles, ankle rolls, and high knees.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes after finishing. Spend 5–8 minutes on static stretching — prioritize hip flexors, glutes, and IT band (lateral leg swings, figure-four stretch, foam roll if available).\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run is the foundation of your week. At VDOT 42, roughly 80% of your weekly running should feel genuinely comfortable — this is one of those sessions. The physiological goal here is building mitochondrial density and aerobic enzyme activity without accumulating fatigue. Think of it as depositing into your aerobic bank account. Given your IT band history, keep the pace honest and avoid cambered roads where possible.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":60,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":290,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jogging for 15 minutes. Include 4 x 20-second strides in the final 3 minutes to prime your neuromuscular system before threshold work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"3 x 8-minute cruise intervals at threshold pace (4:50/km). This should feel comfortably hard — you could speak a word or two but not hold a conversation. Stay relaxed in your shoulders and keep your cadence up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":2,\"notes\":\"2-minute easy jog recovery between each threshold interval. Keep moving — don't stop completely. Use this time to reset your breathing and form.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"10 minutes of easy jogging to flush lactate and begin recovery. Gradual deceleration is important after threshold work.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging. In the last 3 minutes, add 4 x 20-second accelerations (strides) up to threshold pace to prepare your body for the work ahead.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"10 minutes easy jog, then 5–8 minutes of static stretching. Focus on calves, quads, and hip flexors. Hydrate well post-session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Tuesday's threshold session is the quality anchor of your week. Cruise intervals at 4:50/km develop your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain for roughly an hour of racing. For your 1:45 half-marathon goal (approximately 4:59/km race pace), a strong threshold is the single most important physiological adaptation. Three 8-minute reps with 2-minute recoveries is a manageable entry point that builds the system without over-stressing it. The key is consistency of effort across all three reps — if the third rep feels dramatically harder, you may have gone out slightly too fast on rep one.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":387,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Keep this genuinely easy — at or above 6:27/km is perfectly fine today. The goal is active recovery, not fitness building. If your legs feel heavy from Tuesday, that's normal and expected.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed. Start walking for 2 minutes, then ease into a very gentle jog.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes after finishing. This is a great day for foam rolling your IT band, glutes, and calves.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday is a recovery run — and recovery runs only work if they're actually easy. After Tuesday's threshold session, your muscles are in a mild state of repair. A gentle 40-minute run at 6:27/km or slower increases blood flow to aid that repair process without adding meaningful stress. Think of this as active recovery, not a training stimulus. The temptation to push the pace here is real, but resisting it is what makes Thursday and Sunday possible.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":58,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":271,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging. Include 4–6 x 20-second strides in the final 3 minutes, building to interval pace. Your body needs to be genuinely warm before VO2max efforts.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 4-minute intervals at 4:31/km. This is hard — a 9 out of 10 effort. You should feel like you could not sustain this pace much beyond 6 minutes. Stay tall, drive your arms, and focus on smooth turnover rather than forcing the pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"3-minute easy jog recovery between intervals. This is slightly shorter than the work interval — intentional. Incomplete recovery keeps your cardiovascular system elevated and maximizes VO2max stimulus.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"10 minutes easy jogging. Your legs will feel heavy — that's expected. Keep moving to clear metabolic byproducts.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging with 4–6 strides. Do not skip the warmup before VO2max work — cold muscles at high intensity increase injury risk significantly.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"10 minutes easy jog, then thorough stretching. Pay special attention to your IT band today — lateral hip and glute work (clamshells, figure-four) is a good addition post-session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Thursday's VO2max session is the highest-intensity workout of the week. Running at 4:31/km stresses your cardiovascular system near its ceiling, which over time raises that ceiling — meaning your easy and threshold paces become more efficient. For a half-marathon goal, VO2max work is the engine builder. Five 4-minute reps is a solid volume of quality work. The most common mistake here is going out too fast on rep one and fading badly by rep four or five. Aim for even splits or a very slight negative split across the set.\",\"perceived_effort\":9},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":16,\"target_duration_minutes\":100,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":375,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":375,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes very easy — treat this as your warmup even though it's part of the run. Let your body settle in before finding your long run rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":75,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a steady aerobic pace between 5:50–6:27/km. Aim for even effort, not even pace — if there are hills, let your effort guide you rather than your watch. This is where your aerobic base is built.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 15 minutes, ease off slightly. Finish feeling like you had a little left — that's the right long run endpoint.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with 5 minutes of walking, then ease into a very gentle jog. No strides or accelerations before a long run.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after finishing. Prioritize refueling within 30–45 minutes (carbohydrate and protein). Spend 10 minutes on full-body stretching. If you have access to a foam roller, use it on your IT band, quads, and calves.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sunday's long run is the cornerstone of half-marathon preparation. At 16km this week — a modest step up from your recent 14km — the goal is time on feet and aerobic adaptation, not speed. The physiological benefits here include increased glycogen storage capacity, improved fat oxidation, and greater capillary density in your working muscles. All of these directly support your 1:45 goal. Keep the pace genuinely easy: 5:50–6:27/km. If you find yourself pushing toward 5:30, you're working too hard and compromising the adaptation. Bring water or plan a route near fountains — hydration matters on runs over 75 minutes.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
